Force : Push or PullUnit–VII : The World of Things15Let's KnowLet's KnowWe apply force to pull anything towards us. We also apply force to push 
anything away from us. Some example of push and pull are shown in the 
pictures given below–
A push or pull on an object is called force. We can not see the force but we are 
able to do work due to force.
Push 
PullPushEnvironmental Studies-5107

What Can A Force Do?
Force can affect an object in many ways.
1. 
Force can stop a moving object– For 
example, force applied by the foot of a 
player on a moving football stops the ball.
2. 
Force can move a stationary object– For 
example, when a player applies force on 
a football by kicking it, the ball moves.
3. 
Force can increase or decrease the speed of a 
moving object– For example, when we push a 
moving object its speed increases. When we 
apply brakes in our car, its speed decreases.
4. 
Force can change the size and shape of 
an object– For example, when a 
squeeze a toothpaste tube, its shape 
changes.
5. 
Force can change the direction of a moving 
object– For example, when a player hits a moving 
ball with a bat, the ball changes its direction.
In other words, force can move a stationary object and stop a moving object. It can 
also change the speed, direction, size and shape of an object.
Some more examples to understand the effects of force are– 
Environmental Studies-5108

Sometimes a force does not show any effect. For example, when we apply force on 
a wall, it neither moves nor changes its shape or size.
You 
 KnowMust 
(Knowledge)Types of ForcesIn nature, there are two types of forces acting all the times– Gravity and Friction.
1. 
Gravity– The force that pulls all objects downwards towards the centre of the 
earth is called gravity. 
For example, when we throw a ball up in the air, it first rises up, then seems to stop 
and then falls back to the ground. The ball falls back due to the force of gravity.
2. 
Friction– When we push a toy car on a floor, it slows down and stops after 
sometime. The force that acts on it to slow down is called the force of friction. 
Friction opposes movement. It occurs because of rubbing of the object 
against a rough surface. Friction is more on rough surfaces and less on 
smooth surfaces.
Friction is necessary at many places. We can not walk on a polished surface because 
the friction is less. Without friction, we will slip and will not be able to walk.

ActivityActivityAdvantage of Friction–
 
1. 
Friction helps us to walk.
 
2. 
Friction helps us to write. We can not write on polished surfaces.
 
3. 
Friction between road and tyres of automoblies makes their movement 
possible.
Disadvantages of Friction–
 
1. 
It slows down or stops the motion of vehicles. 
 
2. 
It produces heat which damages the parts of machines.
 
3. 
It damages the soles of our shoes and tyres of vehicles.
Thus, we can say that friction has many disadvantages but it is necessary for 
movement.
Environmental Studies-5110

Simple MachinesUnit–VII : The World of Things16Let's KnowLet's KnowA machine is a device or a tool which helps us to do work easily, efficiently and 
fast. Before the invention of sewing machine, people stitched their clothes by 
hand. It was difficult and time consuming. A sewing machine has made 
stitching easier and faster. A knife, scissors, tweezers etc. also help to make 
our work easier and faster. They come under simple machines. Big machines 
like washing machines, cranes, cars, bulldozers etc. are complex machines 
made by joining many simple machines. In this chapter, we shall learn about 
the simple machines.
Simple MachinesSimple machines do work either by changing the direction of force or by reducing 
the effort needed. There are six types of simple machines-the lever, the pulley, the 
inclined plane, the wedge, the wheel and axle, and the screw.
The lever, the inclined plane and the wedge are the oldest known 
machines.
You 
 KnowMust 
(Knowledge)Environmental Studies-5114

! 
A lever is a simple machine which consists of a load, fulcrum and 
Lever– 
effort. The load is the object that is being moved or lifted. The fulcrum is the 
central point and the effort is the force required to lift or move the load.
 
A lever can help to lift up heavy loads and open or 
separate things. See-saw is an example of lever, 
when force is applied to one side, it is pushed 
down and the other side lifts up.
 
A hammer ,a bottle opener, a crowbar and a pair 
of scissors etc. are examples of lever.
! 
A Pulley is a simple machine made with a 
Pulley– 
rope or chain wrapped around a wheel. It changes 
the direction of force and makes it easier to lift things 
to some height. Pulleys are used in drawing water 
from a well, raising a flag on a flagpole, lifting heavy 
weights by a crane etc. 
! 
 An inclined plane is the 
Inclined plane–
sloping or a slanting surface which connects a 
lower level to a higher level. It helps to move 
heavier objects to a height easily. Children's 
slides in a playground, ramps for wheelchairs, 
sloping roads etc. are some examples of 
inclined plane. 
! 
A wedge is a pair of two inclined planes 
Wedge– 
attached back to back forming a sharp edge. This 
egde can slice things apart. For example- knife, an 
axe, a razor or a chisel. 
! 
 A wheel and axle arrangement is 
Wheel and axle–
a simple machine in which a wheel rotates around 
the centre or axle. An axle is usually a smaller 
wheel attached at the centre of a larger wheel.
Environmental Studies-5115

A wheel is not a machine by itself. The wheel and axle must move together to 
form a simple machine. Some common examples of wheel and axle are- tyres 
of vehicles, screwdrivers, door knobs, rolling skates, electric fans, Merry- go -round at a fun fair etc. 
 
A screw is commonly used for holding things together more firmly so that 
they can't be forced to separate. Screws are also used for lifting heavy things.
 
 A Screw Jack is used to lift a car to change its tyre.
For example–

Shelter for AllUnit–VIII : Community Life17Let's KnowLet's KnowA house is one of the basic needs of human beings. It protects us from harsh 
weather, theft and animals. Different types of houses or shelters are seen at 
different places because of the factors like climate of that place, availability of 
building materials, economic status of the house owner etc.
Starter
! Can you recognise this house?
! What is it made of?
! Where is it found?
According to Location and ClimateHilly Regions– Hilly regions receive heavy 
rain and snowfall. These houses usually have 
sloping roofs. This prevents rainwater and 
snow from accumulating on roofs and sliding 
off easily from the roofs. Besides, stones are 
easily available there. Hence, stones are 
mostly used to build houses in these areas.
Polar Regions– In polar regions, the land is 
always covered with ice and snow. The people 
living there called Eskimos,build their houses 
with the blocks of ice and snow. These houses 
are called igloos. The floor or an igloo is covered 
with animal skin to keep it warm.
Environmental Studies-5120

Earthquake Prone Regions– In earthquake prone 
regions like Japan, houses are made up of 
bamboo and wood. These houses cause much 
less damage even if they collapse during an 
Flood Prone Regions– Houses in flood prone areas 
are made on raised platforms, supported by 
wooden pillars called stilts. Stilts keep the house 
safe from flood water. Stilt houses also have 
sloping roofs to allow rainwater to drain off easily.
Hot Regions– In places such as Rajasthan, where 
the climate is very hot, people build houses with 
thick walls, plastered with mud. Their roofs are 
covered with straw or other plant material to save 
the roof from being heated due to sun.
Temporary Houses– Soldiers, scouts and 
mountaineers have to move from one place to 
another. They live in temporary houses known as 
tents. Tents are easy to carry as they are made up 
of a cloth called canvas. Nomads also live in tents.
Houseboats are movable houses that are mostly common in the lakes of 
Kashmir and Kerala.
You 
 KnowMust 
(Knowledge)Environmental Studies-5121According to material AvailableWhen building a house, it is better to use materials that are easily available locally. 
There are two types of houses, based on the material used in them.
Kutcha Houses– Kutcha houses are common in 
villages, These are made up of bamboo, mud, 
straw, wood and dry leaves. The floors are usually 
made of clay and coated with cowdung.

Pucca Houses– Pucca houses are mostly found in cities 
and towns. These houses are more durable. They are 
built of bricks, stones, tiles, iron, glass, marble and 
cement. All these materials are easily available in cities 
and town. These houses are more expensive. 
Pucca houses are of different types–
1. 
Bungalows– Large single-storey 
houses with many rooms, a lawn and a 
porch are called bungalows.
2. 
Multi storey buildings– In big cities, due to 
shortage of space, tall-buildings with many floors 
are constructed. These buildings are called multi- 
storey buildings. These buildings have a number of 
houses on each floor. Each of these houses is 
called a flat or an apartment. 
Animals SheltersJust as people need houses to live in, animals also need a suitable shelter to protect 
themselves from heat ,cold ,rain and to lay eggs, etc.
! Some animals live in natural shelters. Lion, bear, etc live in dens. Elephants, 
rhinocerose etc. live in open or under a tree.
! Some animals make their homes. Birds make their nests, rabbits dig burrows, 
mice dig holes etc.
Environmental Studies-5122

in a shed, dogs live in kennels, horses live in stables, hens live in coops, etc
! Some animals live in water like frogs, fish, turtles, crabs, starfish, octopuses, 
whales, dolphins, etc.
! Some animals fly in air and rest on trees. e.g. birds.
! Ants live in ant-hills. Bees live in hives.
Ÿ A house is one of the basic needs of human beings.
Ÿ The location, climate, availability of material and economic condition of 
people determine the type of house they live in.
Ÿ Animals also need a shelter to live in.

Forest and Tribal Life18A large area of land where numerous trees and bushes grow on their own is 
called a forest. Forests are very important natural resource.
Ÿ They help in purification of air. They give us oxygen.
Ÿ They prevent soil erosion.
Ÿ They give us useful products such as wood, resin, medicines, lac, fruits and 
leaves etc.
Ÿ They support a large variety of life-forms such as humans, animals, birds 
etc.
Besides, many people are also dependent on the forests for their survival and 
livelihood.
Let's KnowLet's KnowUnit–VIII : Community LifeEnvironmental Studies-5126

Tribes of Different StatesTribes live in different parts of India with different traditions, cultures and 
languages. They can be seen in Madhya Pradesh, Odisha, Chhattisgarh, West 
Bengal, Manipur, Nagaland, Meghalaya, Uttarakhand, Andaman and Nicobar 
islands etc. Some well-known tribes are—
Bodos— They belong to Assam. Their main 
occupation is tea plantation and they are the 
best craftsmen of bamboo.
Tribals of IndiaIndia is one of the ten most forest-rich countries of the world. Besides plants and 
animals, forests are home to many people 
too. The people who live in or near the 
forests and are totally dependent on forests 
for their survival are known as Adivasis or 
Tribal people. India is a home to about 437 
tribal communities. These tribal people play 
a major role in forming the cultural heritage 
of India. They are considered to be the true 
inhabitants of India.
The adivasis depend on forests for food, 
shelter and fuel. They collect fruits, nuts, berries and edible roots and hunt animals 
for food. They make clothes from the skin of animals. Wood is used as fuel and to 
make boats.
The adivasis use leaves, barks, gum, lac etc. to make useful items like baskets, mats, 
bows and arrows, ropes etc. They also use them to construct their shelters in the 
forests. The tribal women use grass, seeds, flowers, shells and beads to beautify 
themselves . By using these things they make ornaments like bracelets, necklaces, 
earrings etc.
Environmental Studies-5127

Gonds— They are one of the largest tribes in 
India. They are found in Madhya Pradesh, 
Andhra Pradesh and Odisha. Their main 
occupation is farming and cattle rearing.
Mundas— They are found in West Bengal, 
Odisha, Jharkhand and Bihar. Their main 
occupation is wood cutting and fishing.
Santhals— They are found in Assam, Tripura 
and Bihar. Their main occupation is farming. 
They are also involved in hunting and fishing.
ReligionThe tribals are very religious. They express their faith and religion through art and 
craft. They worship the forces of nature like sun, soil, tree, animals etc. Every tribal 
community has some special trees and animals which are considered sacred. 
These are protected and worshipped.
Some patches of forests are worshipped and are called sacred groves. These groves 
are believed to be associated with deities. The tribals believes that these groves 
protect them from epidemics, wild animals and evil spirits. In different states these 
sacred groves are known by different names like 
deobhumi, devkot, devrai etc.
Bishnois of Rajasthan— The Bishnois (a tribe of 
Rajasthan) are the first in the world for whom 
preservation of animals and plants is a religion. 
Guru Jambheshwar, a great ecologist had made 
principles which included a ban on killing of 
Environmental Studies-5128

animals and felling of trees to protect all life-forms. Amrita Devi, a Bishnoi woman, 
is a very famous conservationist, who used to cling to trees to protest against their 
felling.
Protecting Tribes— Tribal people are totally dependent on forests. They get food, 
fuel, water, timber etc. from the forests they live in. They use bamboos and pine 
trees to make their huts and granaries. They make medicines from things such as 
resin of pine tree and the bark of the cinchona tree. Forests are an important part 
of their social, religious and cultural lives. Deforestation will destroy their homes, 
livelihood and culture. So, to protect them and our cultural heritage, we must 
protect our forests.
The Story of Chipko MovementIn 1973, villagers in the Alaknanda valley in 
Uttarakhand protested against the felling of 
trees in the area. When a sports goods 
manufacturing company wanted to cut down 
trees, the women of the area came forward to 
prevent the felling of trees. They hugged the 
trees and refused to let go till the tree-cutters 
left. This became popular as the Chipko 
Movement. Some of the famous leaders of 
Chipko Movement were Sunderlal Bahuguna, Gaura Devi, Sudesha Devi and 
Chandi Prasad Bhatt.
The ministry of Tribal Affairs takes care of the welfare and 
development of the tribes. It also promotes tribal art and crafts.
